# LINQ guard pipelines over manual loops

When transforming, filtering, or aggregating a sequence, prefer a **LINQ pipeline** with explicit null-safety, instead of `foreach` + a mutable accumulator.

## Preferred

```csharp
List<TenantSummary> active = tenants
    .Where(t => t is { IsActive: true })
    .Select(t => new TenantSummary(t.Id, t.Name))
    .ToList();

bool anyFaulted = runs.Any(r => r.Status is RunStatus.Faulted);

AgentSession? session = sessions.FirstOrDefault(s => s.AgentId == agentId);
if (session is null) return NotFound();

string joined = string.Join(", ", roles ?? []);
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid
List<TenantSummary> active = new();
foreach (Tenant t in tenants)
{
    if (t == null) continue;
    if (!t.IsActive) continue;
    active.Add(new TenantSummary(t.Id, t.Name));
}
```

## When `foreach` still wins

- Awaiting per element (`await foreach`, or per-item `await` when not using `Parallel.ForEachAsync`).
- Writing to multiple sinks per element.
- Hot-path code where a measured allocation cost matters — call it out in a comment.

## Scope

- Pair LINQ filters with `is` patterns for null and shape checks (**`CSharp-Terse-02-PatternMatching.mdc`**).
- Materialize once with `.ToList()` / `.ToArray()` when the source is enumerated more than once.
- Reinforces the existing project rule "prefer LINQ over `foreach` unless it would degrade performance".
